09:08.215 --> 09:12.481
the planning department?

09:16.466 --> 09:16.606
No, no. And what about any direct relationship to 
municipal government? Well, the mayor and the

09:23.036 --> 09:27.642
council gave it encouragement. But I don't think 
they did anything to really implement it. Nor the

09:37.302 --> 09:40.347
county government, nor the school district. 
Neither of them did anything very spectacular to

09:40.367 --> 09:46.275
support it. This comprehensive plan did contain 
several things that had a program for the

09:57.153 --> 09:58.815
restoration of the central city.

10:03.260 --> 10:17.898
It had a plan for an outer belt parkway system at the 
Cayo del Oso, which is a creek on the perimeter of

10:03.260 --> 10:17.898
the city. Nothing has been done with that except 
there have been some committees that have been

10:19.299 --> 10:24.966
working at it. But that's one of the goals and one of 
the challenges that still remain for the city to

10:25.722 --> 10:33.589
do.

10:41.616 --> 10:46.800
Major changes in land use or the school system.

10:50.464 --> 10:54.447
There was a plan for

10:55.895 --> 11:07.052
the

10:55.895 --> 11:07.052
Oso Bay to fill in sections of it and develop it. 
This was unacceptable to the environmental

11:07.072 --> 11:17.046
interests and has not been accomplished. There 
was a feasibility study made to determine if a

11:24.734 --> 11:31.682
offshore roadway could be built from downtown to 
the south end of the city. This proved to be not

11:33.283 --> 11:43.555
feasible.

11:43.575 --> 11:50.522
Offshore road

11:43.575 --> 11:50.522
was several thousand feet off the shore. It had 
islands in connection with it that were could be

11:55.582 --> 12:05.356
developed, both as residential and 
recreational,

11:55.582 --> 12:05.356
with connections into the shoreline. But the plan 
was entirely too expensive and was

12:07.438 --> 12:18.554
environmentally not acceptable.

12:18.574 --> 12:25.183
In 1962,

12:18.574 --> 12:25.183
thereabouts,

12:26.227 --> 12:53.382
The federal government enacted the

12:26.227 --> 12:53.382
federal government provided through the

12:26.227 --> 12:53.382
U.S. Bureau of Public Roads

12:26.227 --> 12:53.382
federal highway agency the opportunity to 
prepare transportation plans for cities. Corpus

12:58.842 --> 13:04.010
Christi was the first city in the United States to 
apply for such a plan. The local district

13:06.574 --> 13:21.597
engineer, Theo Foster, was entirely sympathetic 
and agreed to help us go before the State Highway

13:06.574 --> 13:21.597
Commission and seek approval of the preparation 
of this plan.

13:31.157 --> 13:36.124
Local people went there, the political leaders. 
The Area Development Committee was interested

13:36.966 --> 13:44.917
and helped, but did not take an active part.

13:49.043 --> 13:52.107
We did get approval of the State Highway 
Department. to proceed. The State Highway

13:57.406 --> 14:20.073
Department had no planners on the staff, but 
assigned some very good engineers that were

13:57.406 --> 14:20.073
progressive and wanted to prepare a good plan. The 
city and the county the navigation district, and

14:25.060 --> 14:44.557
all agreed to assist

14:25.060 --> 14:44.557
in the preparation of this plan by providing 
technical assistance and staff.

14:45.498 --> 14:54.105
As city planner, I was assigned to this committee, 
and we had at least two members of our planning

14:54.743 --> 15:04.574
staff that worked with the highway engineers that 
were assigned to this. Do you remember their

15:05.736 --> 15:10.481
names? One of them was

15:10.501 --> 15:15.487
Earl Goetsch. How does he spell that? 
G-O-E-T-S-C-H. He was a senior planner. And we had

15:24.562 --> 15:30.549
the traffic engineer, Tom Stewart. We had public 
works director. And

15:38.299 --> 15:53.117
we had the right to call in as we needed them. of the 
other city staff. The county engineer was on this,

15:56.662 --> 16:06.835
Jesse Lawrence

15:56.662 --> 16:06.835
participated, and we had regular meetings.

16:10.059 --> 16:20.893
And we outlined what should be in the 
transportation plan. And this was a pioneering

16:21.920 --> 16:27.248
effort because it was, and we were considered the 
guinea pig. And so we prepared our outline, which

16:28.890 --> 16:51.522
contained such subjects as economic factors, 
population, land use,

16:28.890 --> 16:51.522
the inventory of transportation facilities, 
studies on travel patterns, terminals and

16:52.463 --> 17:13.972
transfer facilities, traffic engineering, 
community controls, financial resources, and

16:52.463 --> 17:13.972
methods of financing the

16:52.463 --> 17:13.972
plan. And then there was a long range plan for the 
major street system. proposed.

17:25.775 --> 17:31.443
This plan was prepared and completed in 1964. And 
as required by the federal legislation, the city

17:32.224 --> 17:42.778
council was asked to adopt it. And they did. And

17:44.681 --> 17:50.449
they The plan was very well followed, 
particularly as to major streets

17:50.885 --> 17:59.315
and thoroughfares.

